Prunus padus, commonly known as bird cherry, is a deciduous tree in the Rosaceae family. 
It typically grows to a height of 8 to 16 meters. 
The bark is gray-brown and smooth while the leaves are alternately arranged and oval-shaped with a serrated margin. 
The tree blooms in early spring, producing clusters of fragrant, white flowers that emerge before the leaves. 
The fruit is a small, pea-sized drupe that is initially red but turns black when ripe. 
Native to Europe and Asia, bird cherry is commonly found in damp woodlands, hedgerows and along riverbanks. 
It is widely cultivated as an ornamental tree and the fruit is used in jams and beverages.
